      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm looking at our quarterly reports and shrinkage is way higher than last year. how do i actually calculate the impact this has on our inventory turnover ratio? i need the formula to show my boss how much this is messing with our efficiency.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Shrinkage directly impacts your inventory turnover ratio because it means you're selling less product than you think you are, or that your inventory isn't what it seems. You need to adjust your Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) upwards to reflect the actual loss.\n\nHere's the basic formula for Inventory Turnover Ratio:\n\n$$\\text{Inventory Turnover Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)}}{\\text{Average Inventory}}$$\n\nTo show the impact of shrinkage, you need to make sure your COGS is accurate. If shrinkage is high, your reported sales figures might be inflated, or your ending inventory might be understated, which throws the whole ratio off. You need to adjust your COGS to account for the lost goods.",
