    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so if i increase the COGS to include the cost of the lost items, does that make the turnover ratio look lower? basically i'm trying to figure out if the shrinkage is making us look more efficient or less efficient on paper.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, by increasing your Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) to include the cost of those lost items due to shrinkage, you will absolutely make your inventory turnover ratio look **lower**.\n\nA lower turnover ratio generally signals less efficiency. It means it's taking longer to sell off your inventory, or you are moving less stock over the period. If you're losing goods, that's a clear sign of inefficiency, and the lower ratio will highlight that problem for your boss.",
